FOUNDRY IAM

PLATFORM SPECIFICATION

High-Fidelity Engineering & Product Spec v1.0




Classification

INTERNAL — CONFIDENTIAL

Status

APPROVED FOR DEVELOPMENT

Version

1.0.0 — MVP

Target Launch

End of Week (6-day build)

Longevity Target

6–12 months without forced upgrades

Engine

Keycloak 24 (Apache 2.0)



This document is the single source of truth for the Foundry IAM SaaS platform. It covers product scope, system architecture, data model, API contract, infrastructure layout, developer setup, billing model, security posture, and a day-by-day build plan. Any engineer picking up this document should be able to set up, build, and ship without further verbal clarification.



SECTION 1

Product Definition & Scope




1.1 What We Are Building

Foundry IAM is a multi-tenant, developer-first Identity & Access Management platform. It is the Stripe for IAM: a hosted service that lets software teams integrate enterprise-grade authentication and authorisation into their products in under 30 minutes, without operating their own Keycloak cluster or writing a single line of auth plumbing.

Developers sign up, create a Tenant, create an App, copy two environment variables, and have working OIDC login backed by a production-grade Keycloak realm. That is the product.

1.2 What We Are NOT Building (MVP Exclusions)

The following are explicitly deferred. They will not be built in MVP and their absence will not block a paying customer:

SAML — OIDC only for MVP

SCIM provisioning

Custom federation / Bring Your Own IdP UI

Custom login theme builder (single branded theme ships with the platform)

Advanced RBAC UI beyond roles + groups

Multi-region active-active Keycloak

Analytics dashboards beyond MAU counters

Audit log export / SIEM integrations

Marketplace of social providers (Google/GitHub login supported via Keycloak config, not UI-driven)



1.3 The Market Position

Competitor

Our Differentiator

Auth0 / Okta

Best-in-class DX but $8k–$25k/month at scale. Enterprise lock-in.

AWS Cognito

Cheap but brutal DX, rigid, deeply coupled to AWS.

Clerk

Great React DX, limited enterprise isolation, per-MAU pricing climbs fast.

Self-hosted Keycloak

Free engine, $0 licensing, but you own all ops, upgrades, clustering.

Foundry IAM (us)

DX-first. Open standards. No vendor lock-in. 85%+ margin. Affordable enterprise pricing.



1.4 Core Invariants (Must Never Break)

Engineering Law

These invariants define the product contract. Violating them breaks customer integrations and requires a major version bump. They must be enforced via automated tests.



Realm names are deterministic: tnt_<tenantId> for tenant realms, wsp_<workspaceId> for workspace realms

Issuer URL is always: https://id.<domain>/realms/<realmName>

Every realm ships with exactly: tenant_owner, tenant_admin, tenant_billing, tenant_viewer roles

Every realm ships with exactly: owners, admins, billing groups

GET /v1/workspaces/{id}/oidc is the single canonical source of OIDC endpoints

Customers create Workspaces. They never create Realms directly. Realms are an implementation detail.

Public apps always use PKCE. No exceptions.




SECTION 2

System Architecture




2.1 Service Map

The platform is composed of seven discrete services. Each has a single responsibility and communicates over defined interfaces. No service directly accesses another service's datastore.

Service

Role

Port (local)

Tech

keycloak

Identity engine — OIDC/OAuth2 server, realm management

8080

Keycloak 24 + PostgreSQL

api

Control plane — tenant/workspace/app provisioning, billing

3000

Node.js 20 + Express + Prisma

frontend

SaaS portal — tenant dashboard, app setup, docs links

5173

React 18 + Vite + TailwindCSS

docs

Developer documentation site

4000

Docusaurus 3 (static)

postgres

Persistent store — Keycloak DB + Control Plane DB (separate schemas)

5432

PostgreSQL 16

redis

Session cache + rate-limit counters + idempotency keys

6379

Redis 7 (Alpine)

mailpit

Local SMTP trap — catches all outbound email in dev

8025 (UI) / 1025 (SMTP)

Mailpit



2.2 Request Flow — User Login

Browser → Foundry Portal (frontend:5173)

  └─ User clicks 'Sign In'

     └─ Portal redirects to Keycloak realm login page

        └─ Keycloak authenticates user (password / MFA)

           └─ Keycloak issues JWT (access + refresh + id tokens)

              └─ Browser redirected back to Portal with auth code

                 └─ Portal exchanges code for tokens (PKCE flow)

                    └─ Portal stores tokens in memory (never localStorage)

                       └─ Portal calls API with Authorization: Bearer <access_token>

                          └─ API validates token against Keycloak JWKS

                             └─ API extracts tenant_id, workspace_id, roles from claims

                                └─ API returns authorised response



2.3 Request Flow — Tenant Provisioning

Operator calls: POST /v1/tenants

  └─ Control Plane API validates request + checks idempotency key

     └─ API writes Tenant record to control_plane DB (Postgres)

        └─ API calls Keycloak Admin REST API:

           ├─ POST /admin/realms  (create realm tnt_<id>)

           ├─ Apply realm template (password policy, session lifetimes, events)

           ├─ Create realm roles: tenant_owner, tenant_admin, tenant_billing, tenant_viewer

           ├─ Create groups: owners, admins, billing

           ├─ Create portal-mgmt confidential client

           └─ Create owner user + assign to owners group

              └─ API writes Workspace record + realm metadata

                 └─ API publishes TenantProvisioned event to Redis stream

                    └─ API returns 201 with tenant + workspace + OIDC metadata



2.4 Network Topology

Public-facing

frontend (Vite/React), docs (Docusaurus), API /v1/* endpoints, Keycloak /realms/* endpoints

Private (internal only)

Keycloak Admin Console, Keycloak Admin REST API, Redis, Postgres, Mailpit SMTP

Ingress routing

NGINX or Caddy reverse proxy in production. In dev: direct ports via Docker Compose.

TLS

All public endpoints TLS-terminated at proxy. Keycloak configured ssl_required: external.

API → Keycloak

Control plane API communicates with Keycloak Admin REST API using a dedicated service account (master realm, minimal permissions).




