7.3 Critical UX Rules

Engineering Requirement

These UX rules are non-negotiable for the portal to function correctly as an IAM product.



Tokens must NEVER be stored in localStorage or sessionStorage. Store in memory only (React state + oidc-client-ts internal store).

The portal authenticates via the foundry-saas Keycloak realm, NOT the tenant realm. Tenant realms are for customer apps.

Every page must handle token expiry gracefully — silent renew via refresh token before expiry, redirect to login on failure.

The App Detail page is the conversion page. It must show working integration snippets for Node.js, Python, and Go immediately after app creation.

Copy-to-clipboard on all client_id, issuer URL, and jwks_uri values. No manual selection required.

All destructive actions (delete app, revoke invite) require a confirmation modal with typed confirmation string.



7.4 Integration Snippet Template (App Detail Page)

When a developer creates an app, the portal generates ready-to-use code snippets. This is what closes deals. The snippet must be copy-paste runnable — no placeholders left for the developer to figure out.

// Node.js / Express example (auto-populated with real values)

import { expressjwt as jwt } from 'express-jwt'

import jwksRsa from 'jwks-rsa'



export const authMiddleware = jwt({

  secret: jwksRsa.expressJwtSecret({

    jwksUri: 'https://id.foundry-iam.com/realms/tnt_2f8a1d/protocol/openid-connect/certs',

    cache: true,

    rateLimit: true,

  }),

  audience: 'app_7a1f22',

  issuer: 'https://id.foundry-iam.com/realms/tnt_2f8a1d',

  algorithms: ['RS256'],

})



// Access claims in your handler:

// req.auth.sub         → user ID

// req.auth.tenant_id   → 'tnt_2f8a1d'

// req.auth.realm_roles → ['app_user']




