SECTION 11

6–12 Month Longevity Strategy




This platform is designed to run for 6–12 months without a forced feature update. The following choices make that possible.

11.1 Why This Stack Lasts

Decision

Why It Buys Time

Keycloak 24 (Apache 2.0)

Mature, LTS-supported release. No licence cost. Security patches available without major version changes. No vendor dependency.

OpenID Connect + OAuth2

20-year-old internet standards. Customer integrations written against these standards will not break.

PostgreSQL 16

Proven. No surprising deprecations. Prisma handles schema evolution cleanly.

Redis 7

Stable. No breaking changes expected in the 6–12 month horizon.

Node.js 20 LTS

Active LTS until April 2026. No forced upgrades required.

React 18

Stable. No forced upgrade pressure in the target window.

Keycloak realm isolation

Adding new tenants requires zero code changes — purely operational.

API versioning (/v1)

Customer integrations are pinned to v1. Breaking changes go to v2 without disrupting existing customers.



11.2 What Will NOT Need Changing (Unless Customer Demands It)

Core provisioning logic — realm template is stable once validated

OIDC token flow — standards-based, will not break

Billing integration — Stripe API is exceptionally stable

Database schema — additive migrations only, no destructive changes

Docker Compose dev setup — services are pinned to specific image tags



11.3 Operational Playbook (Keeping It Running)

Cadence

Action

Weekly

Review Keycloak security advisories. Apply patch releases (24.x.y) — minor, no downtime.

Monthly

Flush usage counters from Redis to Postgres. Generate Stripe overage invoices. Review error rates in logs.

Quarterly

Review Postgres query performance. Add indexes if slow queries appear. Review Keycloak session counts vs. infrastructure capacity.

Ad hoc

Add new tenant: POST /v1/tenants — no code deployment required. Suspend tenant: PATCH /v1/tenants/:id { status: suspended }.



11.4 When You WILL Need to Upgrade

Triggers for Platform Updates

These events require engineering effort but are predictable and plannable — not emergencies.



Keycloak major version (24 → 25) — migration guide published by Red Hat, typically 2–4 days effort

Customer requests SAML — estimate 5 days to add SAML protocol support

Customer requests SCIM provisioning — estimate 7 days

MAU exceeds 1M — scale Keycloak pods horizontally (no code change, only infra)

Multi-region requirement — architectural change, estimate 2–3 weeks




